Dataset Ranta_1985_10

This dataset from Ranta and Nuutinen (1985) is published in Novak and Stouffer (2020): https://doi.org/10.6084/m9.figshare.12830792.v1

  • Contains n=123 feeding trials.
  • Raw data is not available. We replicated all data from summary statistics.
  • Experiments ran for 10 minutes.
  • Eaten prey were replaced during experiments.
  • We fitted direct FR predictions to the data.
  • Holling-2 was identified as the best fitting model. Other models performed equally.
  • The model predicts a slight preference for prey 2, no switching.
  • No systematic deviations of predicted values were observed.

Prepare data

For both single-species and multi-species experiments, only means & standard deviations of n replicates of an offered prey combination (N01,N02) are available. A full dataset is replicated by drawing numbers of eaten prey from normal distributions with given means and standard deviations and rounded to the next integer. df.all includes all observations, df.multi.rep only multi-species experiments, df.single.1.rep and df.single.2.rep only single-species experiments, respectively.

set.seed(100)

df = read.csv("Ranta_1985_10.csv")

df.single.1 = subset(df, df$Prey2.M==0)
df.single.2 = subset(df, df$Prey1.L==0)
df.multi = subset(df, df$Prey2.M>0 & df$Prey1.L>0 )

df.single.1.rep = data.frame(Prey1=c(),
                             Prey2=c(),
                             Prey1.Eaten=c(),
                             Prey2.Eaten=c()
)

df.single.2.rep = data.frame(Prey1=c(),
                             Prey2=c(),
                             Prey1.Eaten=c(),
                             Prey2.Eaten=c()
)

df.multi.rep = data.frame(Prey1=c(),
                          Prey2=c(),
                          Prey1.Eaten=c(),
                          Prey2.Eaten=c()
)

for(i in 1:nrow(df.single.1)){
  n = df.single.1$n[i]
  Prey1.Eaten = rnorm(n, df.single.1$Prey1.Eaten.Mean[i], df.single.1$Prey1.Eaten.SE[i])
  Prey1.Eaten = round(Prey1.Eaten)
  Prey1.Eaten[Prey1.Eaten<0] = 0
  df.single.1.rep = rbind(df.single.1.rep,
                          data.frame(Prey1=rep(df.single.1$Prey1.L[i],n),
                                     Prey2=rep(0,n),
                                     Prey1.Eaten=Prey1.Eaten,
                                     Prey2.Eaten=rep(0,n)))
}

for(i in 1:nrow(df.single.2)){
  n = df.single.2$n[i]
  Prey2.Eaten = rnorm(n, df.single.2$Prey2.Eaten.Mean[i], df.single.2$Prey2.Eaten.SE[i])
  Prey2.Eaten = round(Prey2.Eaten)
  Prey2.Eaten[Prey2.Eaten<0] = 0
  df.single.2.rep = rbind(df.single.2.rep,
                          data.frame(Prey1=rep(0,n),
                                     Prey2=rep(df.single.2$Prey2.M[i],n),
                                     Prey1.Eaten=rep(0,n),
                                     Prey2.Eaten=Prey2.Eaten))
}

for(i in 1:nrow(df.multi)){
  n = df.multi$n[i]
  Prey1.Eaten = rnorm(n, df.multi$Prey1.Eaten.Mean[i], df.multi$Prey1.Eaten.SE[i])
  Prey2.Eaten = rnorm(n, df.multi$Prey2.Eaten.Mean[i], df.multi$Prey2.Eaten.SE[i])
  Prey1.Eaten = round(Prey1.Eaten)
  Prey2.Eaten = round(Prey2.Eaten)
  Prey1.Eaten[Prey1.Eaten<0] = 0
  Prey2.Eaten[Prey2.Eaten<0] = 0
  df.multi.rep = rbind(df.multi.rep,
                       data.frame(Prey1=rep(df.multi$Prey1.L[i],n),
                                  Prey2=rep(df.multi$Prey2.M[i],n),
                                  Prey1.Eaten=Prey1.Eaten,
                                  Prey2.Eaten=Prey2.Eaten)
  )
}

df.all = data.frame(Prey1 = c(df.single.1.rep$Prey1, df.single.2.rep$Prey1, df.multi.rep$Prey1),
                    Prey2 = c(df.single.1.rep$Prey2, df.single.2.rep$Prey2, df.multi.rep$Prey2),
                    Prey1.Eaten = c(df.single.1.rep$Prey1.Eaten, df.single.2.rep$Prey1.Eaten, df.multi.rep$Prey1.Eaten),
                    Prey2.Eaten = c(df.single.1.rep$Prey2.Eaten, df.single.2.rep$Prey2.Eaten, df.multi.rep$Prey2.Eaten)
)

plot(df.all[, c(1,2)], main="Experimental design")

plot(df.single.1.rep$Prey1, df.single.1.rep$Prey1.Eaten, xlim=c(0,256), ylim=c(0,16), 
     xlab="Prey 1 offered", ylab="Prey 1 eaten", 
     main="Single-species feeding: Prey 1")

plot(df.single.2.rep$Prey2, df.single.2.rep$Prey2.Eaten, xlim=c(0,256), ylim=c(0,16), 
     xlab="Prey 2 offered", ylab="Prey 2 eaten", 
     main="Single-species feeding: Prey 2")

plot(df.multi.rep$Prey1/(df.multi.rep$Prey1+df.multi.rep$Prey2),
     df.multi.rep$Prey1.Eaten/(df.multi.rep$Prey1.Eaten+df.multi.rep$Prey2.Eaten),
     xlim=c(0,1), ylim=c(0,1), 
     xlab="Proportion prey 1 offered", ylab="Proportion prey 1 eaten",
     main="Multi-species preference")
abline(0,1)

Data has to be coded as a named list for Stan. Generic duration of experiments Time=1.0 is provided, and all experiments were conducted with prey replacement Replaced=1.

data.stan = list(n = nrow(df.all),
                 m = 2,
                 N_0 = as.matrix(df.all[, 1:2]),
                 N_e = as.matrix(df.all[, 3:4]),
                 Time = rep(1.0, nrow(df.all)),
                 Replaced = rep(1.0, nrow(df.all))
)

Model fitting

For all models, posterior distributions are sampled using 3 chains, 1000 warmup steps and 2000 sampling steps, each. Initial values init are provided for all parameters. Convergence of MCMC is verified through Rhat value close to 1 and sufficient number of effective samples n_eff.

chains = 3

Fit Holling 2

init = rep(list(list(a = c(1.0,1.0),
                     h = c(1/5,1/5))
),chains)

fit1 = sampling(
  model.H2,
  data = data.stan,
  chains = chains,
  warmup = 1000,
  iter = 3000,
  cores = 3,
  init = init,
  refresh = 100
)
print(fit1, pars=c("a","h"))

Model comparison

Extract log-likelihood values for all fits and compute predictive performance with leave-one-out cross validation using the loo package.

lik1 = extract_log_lik(fit1, merge_chains=FALSE)
reff1 = relative_eff(exp(lik1), cores=4) 
loo1 = loo(lik1, r_eff=reff1, cores=4)

lik2 = extract_log_lik(fit2, merge_chains=FALSE)
reff2 = relative_eff(exp(lik2), cores=4) 
loo2 = loo(lik2, r_eff=reff2, cores=4)

lik3 = extract_log_lik(fit3, merge_chains=FALSE)
reff3 = relative_eff(exp(lik3), cores=4) 
loo3 = loo(lik3, r_eff=reff3, cores=4)

lik4 = extract_log_lik(fit4, merge_chains=FALSE)
reff4 = relative_eff(exp(lik4), cores=4) 
loo4 = loo(lik4, r_eff=reff4, cores=4)

loo_compare(loo1, loo2, loo3, loo4)
       elpd_diff se_diff
model1  0.0       0.0   
model2 -0.6       2.4   
model3 -1.1       2.6   
model4 -1.1       3.3

Posterior predictions for best fitting model

The correct MSFR model function is selected, which has the output (negative) functional response. 1000 samples from the posterior distribution are chosen randomly. Since prey were replaced, predictions are computed directly as feeding rate multiplied by experimental duration. Their median and 90% credible intervals are plotted against observed data.

MSFR = Holling2

n.post = 1000
n.pred = 50
post = as.matrix(fit1)[, 1:4]
set.seed(100)
post = post[sample(1:nrow(post),n.post), ]

Single-species prey 1

N10.pred = seq(0.1, 256, length.out=n.pred)
N1E.pred = matrix(NA, nrow=n.post, ncol=n.pred)

for(k in 1:n.post){
  params = list(a=post[k, 1:2], 
                h=post[k, 3:4],
                m=2)
  for(i in 1:n.pred){
    out = -1.0*unlist(MSFR(t=0, N=c(N10.pred[i], 0.0), parms=params)) 
    N1E.pred[k,i] = out[1]
  }
}

N1E.pred.qs = apply(N1E.pred, 2, function(x) quantile(x, probs=c(0.05, 0.5, 0.95)))

plot(df.single.1.rep$Prey1, jitter(df.single.1.rep$Prey1.Eaten, factor=0.3), 
     xlim=c(0,256), ylim=c(0,18),
     xlab="Prey 1 offered", ylab="Prey 1 eaten",
     main="Single-species feeding: Prey 1")
polygon( c(N10.pred, rev(N10.pred)), 
         c(N1E.pred.qs[1, ], rev(N1E.pred.qs[3, ])), 
         border=NA,
         col=adjustcolor("blue", alpha.f=0.2)
)
lines(N10.pred, N1E.pred.qs[2, ], col="blue", lwd=2)

Single-species prey 2

N2E.pred = matrix(NA, nrow=n.post, ncol=n.pred)

for(k in 1:n.post){
  params = list(a=post[k, 1:2],

                m=2)

  }

N2E.pred.qs = apply(N2E.pred, 2, function(x) quantile(x, probs=c(0.05, 0.5, 0.95)))

plot(df.single.2.rep$Prey2, jitter(df.single.2.rep$Prey2.Eaten, factor=0.3),

Multi-species relative consumption

Multi-species predictions are computed along a gradient of relative composition of N1 and N2 with N1+N2=100.

N0.total = 100

N10.pred = seq(0, N0.total, length.out=n.pred)
N20.pred = N0.total-N10.pred
N1E.pred = matrix(NA, nrow=n.post, ncol=n.pred)
N2E.pred = matrix(NA, nrow=n.post, ncol=n.pred)

for(k in 1:n.post){
  params = list(a=post[k, 1:2], 
                h=post[k, 3:4],
                m=2)
  for(i in 1:n.pred){
    out = -1.0*unlist(MSFR(t=0, N=c(N10.pred[i], N20.pred[i]), parms=params)) 
    N1E.pred[k,i] = out[1]
    N2E.pred[k,i] = out[2]
  }
}

N1E.pred.qs = apply(N1E.pred, 2, function(x) quantile(x, probs=c(0.05, 0.5, 0.95)))
N2E.pred.qs = apply(N2E.pred, 2, function(x) quantile(x, probs=c(0.05, 0.5, 0.95)))

# make relative 
N1E.pred.rel = matrix(NA, nrow=n.post, ncol=n.pred)
N2E.pred.rel = matrix(NA, nrow=n.post, ncol=n.pred)
for(k in 1:n.post){
  N1E.pred.rel[k, ] = N1E.pred[k, ]/(N1E.pred[k, ]+N2E.pred[k, ])
  N2E.pred.rel[k, ] = N2E.pred[k, ]/(N1E.pred[k, ]+N2E.pred[k, ])
}

N1E.pred.rel.qs = apply(N1E.pred.rel, 2, function(x) quantile(x, probs=c(0.05, 0.5, 0.95)))
N2E.pred.rel.qs = apply(N2E.pred.rel, 2, function(x) quantile(x, probs=c(0.05, 0.5, 0.95)))

plot(df.multi.rep$Prey1/(df.multi.rep$Prey1+df.multi.rep$Prey2),
     jitter(df.multi.rep$Prey1.Eaten/(df.multi.rep$Prey1.Eaten+df.multi.rep$Prey2.Eaten),factor=1),
     xlim=c(0,1), ylim=c(0,1),
     xlab="Proportion prey 1 offered", ylab="Proportion prey 1 eaten",
     main="Multi-species preference")
abline(0,1)
polygon( c(N10.pred/N0.total, rev(N10.pred/N0.total)), 
         c(N1E.pred.rel.qs[1, ], rev(N1E.pred.rel.qs[3, ])), 
         border=NA,
         col=adjustcolor("blue", alpha.f=0.2)
)
lines(N10.pred/N0.total, N1E.pred.rel.qs[2, ], col="blue", lwd=2)

The model predicts a slight preference for prey 2.

Additionally, median predicted numbers of eaten prey (N1E and N2E) are computed and plotted against observed data points.

N2E.pred = matrix(NA, nrow=n.post, ncol=nrow(df.multi.rep))

for(k in 1:n.post){

  }
}
